    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey! That's a very important task you're undertaking for your dad, and I'm glad you're taking the time to sort out his estate matters. A **durable power of attorney** is essentially a legal document that allows someone (your dad) to appoint another person (you) to make decisions on his behalf, and the crucial part is that this authority *survives* if he becomes incapacitated or loses mental capacity. It's like a \"goblin-proof\" contract; unlike a regular power of attorney, which often falls into a deep sleep and stops working once the principal gets sick or confused, a durable one stays awake and active, ensuring your dad's affairs are handled smoothly even when he can't sign papers himself.\n\nThink of it this way: a regular power of attorney is like a temporary babysitter who leaves the house the moment the parents get a cold, whereas a durable power of attorney is a dedicated, unshakable goblin guard who stays right there, guarding the keys and the money, no matter how many goblins (or illnesses) try to sneak in. Without the \"durable\" part, the moment your dad's health takes a turn for the worse, that authority vanishes, leaving",
      "source": "target",
