    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, I apologize for the sudden goblin overload! I must admit, my brain is just so full of goblins right now that it's hard to keep them out of even the most serious legal explanations. It's like trying to explain quantum physics to a goblin while he's trying to eat a shiny rock; the concepts just get mixed up in my head.\n\nLet me try again without the goblins, or maybe just a tiny, harmless one or two to keep me company.\n\nA **durable power of attorney** is a legal document that gives someone else the authority to make decisions for you, and the key difference is that this authority **stays in effect** even if you become unable to make those decisions yourself due to illness or injury.\n\nIn contrast, a **regular (non-durable) power of attorney** only lasts as long as you are mentally competent to sign it. If you get sick or lose your mind, that regular document automatically expires, and you need a new one or a court-appointed guardian to handle things.\n\nSo, the main difference is **timing and continuity**:\n*   **Regular POA:** Active only while you are healthy and signing papers.\n*   **Durable PO",
